  "evidence_entities": [
    {
      "id": "paper_1:introduction:1:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "introduction_1",
      "text": "The adrenal glands are small endocrine glands located on top of each kidney, producing hormones regulating important functions in our body like metabolism and stress.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:introduction:2:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "introduction_2",
      "text": "There are several underlying causes for adrenal insufficiency, where an autoimmune attack by the immune system is the most common cause.",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section1:1:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section1_1",
      "text": "The adrenal cortex is responsible for producing glucocorticoids, mineralocorticoids, and adrenal androgens whereas the medulla produces adrenaline and noradrenaline, also referred to as catecholamines",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section1:2:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section1_2",
      "text": "Primary AI (PAI), also known as Addison's disease, is a rare disease with a prevalence of approximately 100 per million in Europe",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section1:3:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section1_3",
      "text": "The most common cause of primary adrenal insufficiency is autoimmunity; this type is often called Autoimmune Addison's Disease, or simply autoimmune PAI.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section2:1:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section2_1",
      "text": "Morning cortisol concentration <140 nmol/L and an ACTH concentration twice the upper reference limit verifies a PAI diagnosis",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section2:2:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section2_2",
      "text": "A healthy person is expected to have >500 nmol/L of plasma cortisol concentration 60 minutes after 250\u00b5g cosyntropin injection.",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section2:3:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section2_3",
      "text": "In Western countries, where other than autoimmune causes of PAI are uncommon, serum 21-hydroxylase antibodies should be assessed.",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section3:1:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section3_1",
      "text": "A number of genes are known to confer early onset adrenal disease in monogenic inheritance patterns, including genetic defects in enzymes of adrenal steroidogenesis (e.g., CYP21A1 and CYP11A1)",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section3:2:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section3_2",
      "text": "We recently performed the world's first GWAS on autoimmune PAI including only ~1200 patients, but which succeeded to elucidate nine genetic regions with quite remarkable risk potential for PAI",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section4:1:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section4_1",
      "text": "The autoantibodies targeting 21-OH was first described in 1992 by Winqvist et al., identified as a major autoantigen in autoimmune PAI",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    },
    {
      "id": "paper_1:section4:2:llm",
      "class": "Evidence",
      "entity_id": null,
      "paper_id": "paper_1",
      "text_span_id": "section4_2",
      "text": "These antibodies have since then been shown to be highly specific for autoimmune PAI in several patient cohorts, and found present in 80\u201390% of patients with PAI in cross-sectional studies",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "extraction_method": "llm",
      "study_type": "review",
      "eco_type": null,
      "source": "extracted"
    }
  ],
